			<div class="content" id="post-content-2739956">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Square&nbsp;your&nbsp;shoulders,&nbsp;lift&nbsp;your&nbsp;pack,&nbsp;and&nbsp;leave&nbsp;your&nbsp;friends&nbsp;and&nbsp;go...</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">&nbsp;</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/now-hollow-fires-burn-out-to-black-and-lights-are-waning-low">Believe it or not I did some research for my latest tale</a></p>
<p>I came into writing that tale with the idea of light and darkness being a primary theme affecting the setting. That said, I was also thinking about where to place my tale in the context of a Western canon I was working on. On thing was clear: I wanted to open the tale with an eclipse (I eventually added a scene preceeding the eclipse).</p>
<p>I googled &quot;Eclipses in the 1870's&quot; and this was the first page that came up on google: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_eclipse_of_December_22,_1870">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_eclipse_of_December_22,_1870</a></p>
<p>On the right it showed the path of the eclipse, and it obviously didn't fit since it came nowhere near the western US. I scrolled down the page and noticed that wikipedia also documented all eclipses by date (with an index at the bottom of each page). So I checked all of them (about five in total) until I found this: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_eclipse_of_July_29,_1878">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_eclipse_of_July_29,_1878</a> .</p>
<p>That one went over the old west. So I clicked through to the references and found this: <a href="https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsearch/SEsearchmap.php?Ecl=18780729">https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEsearch/SEsearchmap.php?Ecl=18780729</a></p>
<p>That's a zoomable map showing the exact path of the eclipse. I zoomed in on southern Wyoming, where I *wanted* to put my story, and it worked out that the eclipse passed right over that area. From that I could work out that the town of Riddle, the setting of my story, was somewhere between Rock Springs and Cheyenne, and the closest town would be Rawlins. It also set the date of my tale's primary action as August 1878.</p>
<p>Next up I kinda wanted to see about grabbing a period newspaper article that fit the theme of my tale. So I googled &quot;Wyoming newspapers&quot;. First hit was this: <a href="http://newspapers.wyo.gov/">http://newspapers.wyo.gov/</a></p>
<p>That site has a searchable index of newspapers and keeps scans of historical newspapers online. A search for &quot;1878 eclipse&quot; got me here: <a href="http://pluto.wyo.gov/awweb/main.jsp?flag=collection&amp;un=public&amp;ps=public&amp;smd=1&amp;cl=library2_lib&amp;qs=1878+eclipse&amp;qt=16&amp;submit=Search+Newspapers&amp;itype=advs&amp;menu=on">http://pluto.wyo.gov/awweb/main.jsp?flag=collection&amp;un=public&amp;ps=public&amp;smd=1&amp;cl=library2_lib&amp;qs=1878+eclipse&amp;qt=16&amp;submit=Search+Newspapers&amp;itype=advs&amp;menu=on</a></p>
<p>After that I searched through the newspapers I finally came across this from the day after the eclipse in the Laramie Daily Sentinel (which is also fairly close to my tale's setting): <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/local--files/now-hollow-fires-burn-out-to-black-and-lights-are-waning-low/18780730770004.pdf">http://www.scp-wiki.net/local--files/now-hollow-fires-burn-out-to-black-and-lights-are-waning-low/18780730770004.pdf</a> .</p>
<p>I downloaded it and read the whole page (the eclipse story starts at the top of the third column from the left). I also cut out part of the story to use on the tale itself (though I didn't end up using it after all).</p>
<p>This whole process left me with a better understanding of my setting and the time in which my tale took place.</p>
<p>Since the story features someone who in mainstream continuity kills plants by his very presence, I wanted him to spend most of his time in a desert, so I could leave that up in the air. A little bit of research into my setting of southern Wyoming led me to learn about the Red Desert which is perfectly placed with regards to the fictional location of Riddle. It is name-checked in the tale.</p>
<p>Oh. Also when writing the fake Abraham Lincoln speech that opens the tale I looked up both the actual Gettysburg Address and several pieces on Lincoln's speaking style. The fact that he tended to speak in biblical metaphors and language (which I learned in this research) was in my mind as I wrote the fake speech. I think it added a bit of authenticity to the thing.</p>
<p>Anyway. I think every single step here helped make my tale <strong>better</strong>. So that's why you research. I have stories like this for almost every skip and tale I've written. And I've written a lot.</p>
</div>
